#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:5
msgid "Industrial IIO device buffers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:8
msgid "1. Overview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:10
msgid ""
"The Industrial I/O core offers a way for continuous data capture based on a "
"trigger source. Multiple data channels can be read at once from ``/dev/iio:"
"deviceX`` character device node, thus reducing the CPU load."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:14
msgid ""
"Devices with buffer support feature an additional sub-directory in the ``/"
"sys/bus/iio/devices/iio:deviceX/`` directory hierarchy, called bufferY, "
"where Y defaults to 0, for devices with a single buffer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:19
msgid "2. Buffer attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:21
msgid ""
"An IIO buffer has an associated attributes directory under ``/sys/bus/iio/"
"iio:deviceX/bufferY/``. The attributes are described below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:25
msgid "``length``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:27
msgid ""
"Read / Write attribute which states the total number of data samples "
"(capacity) that can be stored by the buffer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:31
msgid "``enable``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:33
msgid ""
"Read / Write attribute which starts / stops the buffer capture. This file "
"should be written last, after length and selection of scan elements. Writing "
"a non-zero value may result in an error, such as EINVAL, if, for example, an "
"unsupported combination of channels is given."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:39
msgid "``watermark``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:41
msgid ""
"Read / Write positive integer attribute specifying the maximum number of "
"scan elements to wait for."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:44
msgid "Poll will block until the watermark is reached."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:46
msgid ""
"Blocking read will wait until the minimum between the requested read amount "
"or the low watermark is available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:49
msgid ""
"Non-blocking read will retrieve the available samples from the buffer even "
"if there are less samples than the watermark level. This allows the "
"application to block on poll with a timeout and read the available samples "
"after the timeout expires and thus have a maximum delay guarantee."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:55
msgid "Data available"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:57
msgid ""
"Read-only attribute indicating the bytes of data available in the buffer. In "
"the case of an output buffer, this indicates the amount of empty space "
"available to write data to. In the case of an input buffer, this indicates "
"the amount of data available for reading."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:63
msgid "Scan elements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:65
msgid ""
"The meta information associated with a channel data placed in a buffer is "
"called a scan element. The scan elements attributes are presented below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:68
msgid "**_en**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:70
msgid ""
"Read / Write attribute used for enabling a channel. If and only if its value "
"is non-zero, then a triggered capture will contain data samples for this "
"channel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:74
msgid "**_index**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:76
msgid ""
"Read-only unsigned integer attribute specifying the position of the channel "
"in the buffer. Note these are not dependent on what is enabled and may not "
"be contiguous. Thus for userspace to establish the full layout these must be "
"used in conjunction with all _en attributes to establish which channels are "
"present, and the relevant _type attributes to establish the data storage "
"format."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:82
msgid "**_type**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:84
msgid ""
"Read-only attribute containing the description of the scan element data "
"storage within the buffer and hence the form in which it is read from "
"userspace. Format is [be|le]:[s|u]bits/storagebits[Xrepeat][>>shift], where:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:88
msgid "**be** or **le** specifies big or little-endian."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:89
msgid "**s** or **u** specifies if signed (2's complement) or unsigned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:90
msgid "**bits** is the number of valid data bits."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:91
msgid ""
"**storagebits** is the number of bits (after padding) that it occupies in "
"the buffer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:93
msgid ""
"**repeat** specifies the number of bits/storagebits repetitions. When the "
"repeat element is 0 or 1, then the repeat value is omitted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../iio/iio_devbuf.rst:95
msgid ""
"**shift** if specified, is the shift that needs to be applied prior to "
"masking out unused bits."
msgstr ""

